rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
rdf:Description.igem:author: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
rdf:Description.igem:note:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS.
Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
rdf:Description.igem:description: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Reshma Shetty
rdf:Description.igem:source: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
rdf:Description.igem:note:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_B0011
rdf:Description.igem:description: Bidirectional transcriptional terminator consisting of a 22 bp stem-loop.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Reshma Shetty
rdf:Description.igem:source: Derived from luxICDABEG operon terminator of Vibrio fischeri <genbank>AF170104</genbank>.
rdf:Description.igem:note: In the naturally-occuring sequence there is a mismatch in the stem of the stem loop. This can be corrected via an A->G mutation (at position 40 -- sequence coordinate/not MFOLD coordinate). The above sequence does not reflect this mutation (but the MFOLD image does). This terminator's location cannot be found using some inverted repeat detectors like PALINDROME because it is too short and contains a mismatch. This one was found with the help of Tom Knight. It lies between two coding regions that point towards eachother.

rdf:Description.igem:description: Coding region for the cI repressor based on cI repressor from bacteriophage lambda modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein. cI repressor binds to the cI regulator (BBa_R0051).
rdf:Description.igem:author: Vinay S Mahajan, Brian Chow, Peter Carr, Voichita Marinescu and Alexander D. Wissner-Gross
rdf:Description.igem:source: Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_K091104
rdf:Description.igem:description: This promoter is a modified version of the Mnt promoter that is also responsive to LacI. The promoter should be repressed by Mnt repressor. It should also be repressed by LacI, and in the absence of Mnt repressor, should be induced by IPTG.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Robert Cool
rdf:Description.igem:source: This part comes from the Mnt promoter and the LacI promoter
rdf:Description.igem:note: Mnt repressor binds as a tetramer to two half-operator sites. Introduction of a LacI binding site between the Mnt promoter -10 sequence and the start site for transcription should allow for repression by LacI. Accordingly, the hybrid promoter was designed by 1) Remove all bases of mnt promoter 3??? to -10: gagtcgtattaattt will be replaced by tgtgtggaattgtga, and 2) Position lacI binding site (composed of an inverted repeat) from the lacI regulated promoter (R0010) immediately 3??? to truncated mnt promoter.

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_K091107
rdf:Description.igem:description: This hybrid promoter is designed to respond to activation by LuxR when it is bound to AHL and to repression by the phage lambda cI repressor. The repression needs to win over activation.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Xiao Zhu
rdf:Description.igem:source: this part comes from LuxR promoter and cI lambda promoter.
